In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April as National Sexual Assault Awareness and Prevention Month. He emphasizes that sexual assault is a crime that affects all communities and calls for everyone to play a role in protecting their loved ones. The President highlights the progress made in reducing stigma and providing support to survivors, particularly through the Violence Against Women Act. However, he acknowledges that sexual violence remains a common tragedy, with one in five women being sexually assaulted in college. To address this issue, he launched the White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault and proposed funding for addressing the backlog of rape kits. The President emphasizes the importance of stopping sexual assaults in both civilian and military contexts and highlights the impact these crimes have on individuals and society as a whole. He urges Americans to recognize their stake in preventing sexual assault and to support survivors. The article ends with the official proclamation designating April 2014 as National Sexual Assault Awareness and Prevention Month.